msIdentifier.repository: Kislak Center for Special Collections, Rare Books and Manuscripts

msContents.summary: Collection of astronomical works, including works on the astrolabe, horoscopes, risings and settings of the planets.

author.persName: Shīrāzī, Ḥaydar ibn Muḥammad, active 13th century-14th century
Fārsī, Taqī al-Dīn Muḥammad ibn Muḥammad, active 16th century
فارسى، تقى الدين محمد بن محمد،

msItem.title: On the eclipse of the moon from the sayings of the Prophet Daniel, f. 21r
Collection of treatises and tables, f. 22r
On astronomy and the astrolabe, f. 163r

supportDesc.extent: 168 leaves : 194 x 128 mm. bound to 196 x 135 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Paper, i + 168 + i; [1-168], modern foliation in pencil, upper left recto.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in varying numbers of long lines.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in nastaʻlīq by multiple hands in black ink; pointed.

decoDesc.decoNote: Ink drawings in the Dhakhīrat Iskandar Dhū al-Qarnayn of an animal, perhaps a jackal (f. 149v), 2 worms with pincers (f. 150v), hybrids of a snake with an animal's head and a person with a snake's tail (f. 151r), a scorpion (f. 151v), a crane (f. 152v), a youth with one hand on his head (f. 153r), and a rougher, sexual drawing of a man and a woman (f. 154v); tables in red and black (f. 41r-107r); significant words or phrases and headings in red throughout.
Drawing, Serpent with animal's head, f. 151r
Drawing, Man with serpent's tail, f. 151r
Drawing, Youth with one hand on his head, f. 153r
Drawing, Sexual drawing of man and woman, f. 154v

binding.p: Black leather (Type III) with painted gilt borders, stamped with a central mandorla and four pendants on the vertical axis, the middle two pendants bear the name Ibrāhīm ibn Muḥammad Bāqir; red leather doublure with gold painted central floral cross and frame.

origin.p: Some works dated 1081 A.H. (1670 CE), mention they were copied in the madrasah of ʻAlī Jāh Maḥmūd Beg Nāẓir (f. 136v, 157r, 168v), probably in Iṣfahān (f. 136v) in Persia, now Iran.

history.provenance: Formerly owned by Muḥammad ʻAlī al-Iṣfahānī, Muḥarram [1]126? A.H. (note f. 1r, stamps f. 1r-2r, 21r, 22r, 42v, 65v, 137v, 163r, 168v).
Formerly owned by Prince Sadruddin Aga Khan; sold at auction as part of his collection at Piasa (Paris), 7 June 1999.
Sold by Sam Fogg Ltd. (London) to Lawrence J. Schoenberg, Mar. 2001.
Deposit by Lawrence J. Schoenberg and Barbara Brizdle, 2011.
